  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Every differentiable function is continuous.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        A function is continuously differentiable if it is differentiable and its derivative is continuous.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        A function is of differentiability class <m>C^{k}</m> if the derivatives <m>f',f'',\cdots,f^{(k)}</m> exist and are continuous.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>C^{0}</m>: continuous functions
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>C^{1}</m>: continuously differentiable functions
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>C^{\infty}</m>: smooth functions
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>C^{\omega}</m>: analytic functions. (May not put this here in the end.)
            </p>

            <p>
              An example of a function that is smooth but not analytic is the bump function
              <me>
                f(x)=\begin{cases}\ee^{-\frac{1}{1-x^2}}&#x26;\text{if $|x|&#x3C;1$}\\ 0&#x26;\text{otherwise}\end{cases}
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Often interesting example:
        <me>
          g_{n}(x)=\begin{cases}x^{n}\sin(1/x)&#x26;\text{if $x\neq 0$}\\ 0&#x26;\text{if $x= 0$}\end{cases}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Remind about Intermediate Value Theorem, which can now be proven using known tools
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Darbouxâ€™s theorem: Suppose <m>f:[a,b]\to\bb R</m> is differentiable.
        If <m>\alpha</m> is between <m>f'(a)</m> and <m>f'(b)</m>, there exists <m>c\in(a,b)</m> such that <m>f'(c)=\alpha</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
